{
  "slug": "the-10-best-horror-movies-of-the-year-so-far-plus-the-new-sc",
  "title": "The 10 Best Horror Movies of the Year … So Far. Plus: The New Scary Movie Royalty, and ‘Obsession,’ With Curry Barker!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Chris Ryan"
  ],
  "published": "2026-05-15",
  "runtimeMin": 130,
  "format": "Sean and Chris Ryan look at horror's midpoint on the way to Halloween: the YouTube-to-multiplex pipeline turning directors in their mid-20s into names, and a ranking of who runs the genre now. Then a rundown of 2026 so far, from the headliner 'Obsession' to festival pickups and 80-minute Shudder oddities. Closes with Sean's interview with Curry Barker about 'Obsession.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The state of horror",
      "note": "the YouTube pipeline, and the genre's new royalty",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Backrooms",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Kane Parsons' feature from his own Creepypasta/YouTube series, with Chiwetel Ejiofor attached. Sean calls it the big test of whether a YouTube fandom converts to a $35M opening."
        },
        {
          "title": "Alpha",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Julia Ducournau's new one, less horror than body-psychosis drama and an AIDS parable. Sean found it dour, missing the mania of 'Raw' and 'Titane.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mother of Flies",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The Adams family's latest (Catskills DIY horror). Chris: very disgusting, very effective. On Shudder now."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bodycam",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Brandon Christensen, whom Chris flags as up-and-coming. 75 minutes but stretched; 'a really good episode of Tales From the Crypt.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The 2026 horror roundup",
      "note": "the year so far, movie by movie",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Obsession",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "The headliner. Curry Barker's monkey's-paw romance: a hopeless-romantic breaks a 'one wish willow' to win his crush, then pays for it. Both raved about Indy Navarrete, trapped inside her own body; darker and less funny than expected."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hokum",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Damian McCarthy (Caveat, Oddity), the classical Shudder formalist. Adam Scott as a dickhead fantasy author at a haunted Irish hotel. Right structure, great whodunit, but never elevates; too tidy."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Mummy",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Lee Cronin's third feature and biggest, ~$22-25M. Really an Exorcist movie about a possessed girl; incredibly gross, high-tension. Two hours 17 is the unforgivable sin, and its Egypt/West framing feels made in the '80s."
        },
        {
          "title": "Exit 8",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Genki Kawamura's Japanese video-game adaptation (Neon). A man loops through an inescapable subway passage; labyrinthine dread for 75 minutes before it explains its trauma arc. The lockers full of babies got Chris."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mārama",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Towa Stafford's chamber piece (XYZ): a young Maori woman sails 90 days to 1860 England to find her sister, into a nefarious host's house. Ariana Osborn is amazing; extraordinary style on a small budget."
        },
        {
          "title": "Is God Is",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Aleshea Harris adapting her own Obie-winning play (Amazon, in theaters). Twin sisters scarred as children are sent by their dying mother to hunt their father. A Kill Bill revenge road movie; Sterling K. Brown, Vivica A. Fox. 'Fucking good.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Undertone",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Ian Tewison (now rebooting Paranormal Activity). Shows nothing, largely without incident, but the intimate dread plays better solo with AirPods than in a theater. 80 minutes that feels like two hours."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dolly",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Rod Blackhurst. The opposite of Undertone: shows everything, makes you sit in the pain. A strong malevolent villain in Fabianne Therese. Also feels padded past its 80 minutes."
        },
        {
          "title": "Affection",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "A good Jessica Rothe performance and a wild premise, reminiscent of Frankenheimer's 'Seconds.' The first 40 minutes grip; then at the 50-minute mark it tells you exactly what it is."
        },
        {
          "title": "Faces of Death",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Daniel Goldhaber's remake, maybe Sean's favorite horror movie of the year. About our fascination with extremity and the person moderating that content; less snuff than a commentary on it. 'Goldhaber's got some juice.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "28 Years Later: The Bone Temple",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Chris's likely movie of the year so far, if you count it as horror. Terrifying."
        },
        {
          "title": "Primate",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "A quick rave: Chris 'had a ball' with it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Send Help",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Another one Chris had a ball with."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dooba Dooba",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Skinamarink-adjacent CCTV/security-cam horror: a babysitting job the sitter can't leave. 75 minutes, a little long, but scary when it's scary, and silly by design."
        },
        {
          "title": "Cold Storage",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "An '80s-feeling sci-fi/gross-out creature feature with Joe Keery. Reminded Chris of the remake of 'The Blob.' Fun."
        },
        {
          "title": "Do Not Enter",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Social-media urban-explorers break into a haunted, mole-people-infested Atlantic City casino chasing hidden money. Part of horror's current run on influencers going where they shouldn't."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Curry Barker",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Obsession",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "The Alabama-raised, YouTube-bred writer-director on the monkey's-paw idea (sparked by a Simpsons episode, not the 1902 story), directing Indy Navarrete to play 'crazy jealous girlfriend' instead of demon, keeping the lore unexplained, and choosing not to cast himself. Under $1M, acquired out of TIFF's Midnight Madness in a Neon/A24/Focus bidding war."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anything But Ghosts",
          "year": 2027,
          "note": "His next film (Focus), a buddy comedy he stars in with Cooper Tomlinson as two ghost hunters who find real ghosts. Also features Aaron Paul and Bryce Dallas Howard."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
